<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-666-725  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 666 725.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Nov 26 1990 n494 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Speaking on platforms. (global computing configurations for the1990s) (Viewpoint)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rogers, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computing environment of the 1990s involves a singlecross-application network structure that allows users to accessinformation wherever they reside on the network.andP;  Organizationscan take advantage of varying computer platforms with applicationssoftware that not only coexists with networks and client/serverarchitectures, but exploits them.andP;  In order for cross-platformcomputing and heterogeneous networks to benefit end-users,organizations must take a number of steps.andP;  Companies shouldprocure a cross-platform implementation of networked applications.andO;A consistent interface across different platforms makes migrationto a new environment easier for users.andP;  To ensure cross-platformintegration, organizations must employ a sophisticated suite ofconnectivity technologies that are included in its applicationsoftware.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ArchitectureMultivendor SystemsSoftware EngineeringNetwork ManagementFuture of ComputingConnectivity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>